value.value: any anomaly in the urinary amount of catecholamines, including adrenaline, noradrenaline and L-dopamine; catecholamines are act as hormones or neurotransmitters and are derived from the amino acid tyrosine
any anomaly in the amount of catecholamines, including adrenaline, noradrenaline and L-dopamine; catecholamines are act as hormones or neurotransmitters and are derived from the amino acid tyrosine
any anomaly in the wavelike sequence of involuntary muscular contraction and relaxation that passes along the ureter, thus propelling urine from the kidney pelvis to the urinary bladder
adhesion of the iris to the cornea
adhesion of the iris to the capsule of the lens or to the surface of the vitreous body

presence of adhesions (synechiae) between the Bowman's capsule and the glomerular tuft; may develop when areas of glomerular capillary basement membrane denuded of visceral epithelial cells come in contact with the parietal epithelium of Bowman's capsule
any structural anomaly of the epithelial lining of the luminal space of the ureter
any structural anomaly of the epithelial lining of the luminal space of the urethra

an abnormally placed opening of the ureter, either into the urinary bladder or at another site in the lower urinary or genital tract; commonly a result of a duplicated renal collecting system, a duplex kidney with two ureters where usually one ureter terminates at the urinary bladder, while the duplicated ureter being ectopic, ends in the vagina, the urethra or the vulval vestibule
any structural anomaly of the junction between the ureter and the renal pelvis of the kidney

any structural anomaly of the valve-like structure found at the site of entry of the ureter into the urinary bladder, normally displays an oblique angulation through the detrusor to avoid reflux of urine up the ureters and the kidney
congenital absence or closure of the connection between the ureter and the renal pelvis
a constriction or narrowing of the junction between the ureter and the renal pelvis
a partial or total blockage of the flow of urine through the junction of the renal pelvis and the proximal ureter
a partial or total blockage of the valve-like structure found at the site of entry of the ureter into the urinary bladder

two ureters open separately into the renal pelvis superiorly and drain separately into the urinary bladder or genital tract; if two ureteral buds arise from the Wolffian duct, a duplex kidney with complete ureteral duplication ensues where the additional ureter may result in a ureterocele, or an ectopic ureter
hair and/or skin coloration shows specific and consistent deviations from an expected display
any anomaly in the characteristic surface outline or contour of a head of an organism
anomaly in the average size of the portion of the body containing the brain and organs of sight, hearing, taste, and smell

label.value: abnormal glomerular capsule visceral layer morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the inner layer of the glomerular capsule surrounding the capillary endothelial cells and composed of highly specialized epithelial cells (podocytes) that are separated by filtration slits; the visceral layer is separated from the outer parietal layer by the urinary space (also known as the Bowman's or capsular space)

label.value: abnormal glomerular capsule parietal layer morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the outer layer of the glomerular capsule composed of a single layer of simple squamous epithelium

any structural anomaly of the luminal region between the glomerular capsule visceral and parietal layers, into which filtrate enters after passing through the filtration barrier from the glomerular capillaries

reduced volume of the luminal region between the glomerular capsule visceral and parietal layers, into which filtrate enters after passing through the filtration barrier from the glomerular capillaries

increased volume of the luminal region between the glomerular capsule visceral and parietal layers, into which filtrate enters after passing through the filtration barrier from the glomerular capillaries

a metaplastic change or transformation of the single layer of the parietal epithelium of Bowman's capsule from the normal structural appearance of simple squamous epithelium to a cuboidal or low columnar epithelium; also referred to as a prominent parietal epithelium
an expansion in the volume of the portion of the small intestine that extends from the duodenum to the ileum
any structural anomaly of any of the several elongated bones of the extremities
a skeletal dysplasia characterized by the bending of the long bones of the extremities

formation of a crescent-shaped (semi-lunar) glomerular lesion corresponding to extracapillary proliferation of Bowman's capsular epithelium and acquiring a fibroblast-like spindled morphology, possibly stimulated by release of fibrinogen from a ruptured glomerular basement membrane; epithelial crescents occur in aggressive forms of glomerulonephritis, may be accompanied by collagen and fibrin deposition and/or monocyte and macrophage proliferation, may protrude into Bowman's space, and ultimately compress and destroy the glomerular tuft
formation or presence of a thrombus within the blood vessel network of the organ of secretion
formation or presence of a thrombus within the renal glomerular capillaries
stretched or widened aperture of the luminal space of the small branching blood vessel in the kidney glomerulus that receives blood from the kidney afferent arteriole
spreading of mesangial cells into the contiguous space between the adjacent glomerular endothelial cells and the glomerular basement membrane (GBM)

any structural anomaly of the first branch of the left and right subclavian arteries that merge to form the single midline basilar artery; branches of the vertebral arteries supply the musculature of the neck
bleeding into the skin

a smooth, moderately sized hemorrhagic area, typically dark red to reddish purple, resulting from extarvasation of blood into the skin, mucous membrane, or serosal surface; a pupura becomes brown-yellow as it fades and does not blanch on applying pressure

high urinary levels of aspartylglucosamine, a derivative of aspartic acid; caused by deficient activity of the enzyme N-aspartyl-beta-glucosaminidase (aspartylglucosaminidase) which normally cleaves long sugar chains known as oligosaccharides in the lysosome

abnormally high levels of oxalic acid or oxalates in the urine; many metal ions form insoluble precipitates with oxalate, a prominent example being calcium oxalate, the primary constituent of the most common kind of kidney stones

any anomaly in the directed movement of a motile cell guided by a specific chemical concentration gradient; movement may be towards a higher concentration (positive chemotaxis) or towards a lower concentration (negative chemotaxis)
anomaly in the size of the structure where embryonic blood vessels are surrounded by trophoblast cells and maternal blood
increase in the size of the structure where embryonic blood vessels are surrounded by trophoblast cells and maternal blood
reduction in the size of the structure where embryonic blood vessels are surrounded by trophoblast cells and maternal blood

any structural anomaly of the vascularized and branched structures arising from the rodent trophoblast-derived epithelium that allow an increase its surface area for the efficient exchange of nutrients and wastes between the maternal and fetal circulation
decrease in the width of the structure where embryonic blood vessels are surrounded by trophoblast cells and maternal blood
increase in the width of the structure where embryonic blood vessels are surrounded by trophoblast cells and maternal blood

label.value: abnormal placenta intervillous maternal lacunae morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the spaces of the placenta occupied by maternal blood, into which the fetal labyrinth villi project

label.value: abnormal placenta fetal blood space morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the spaces of the placenta occupied by fetal blood, primarily within the fetal labyrinth villi
derangement of the placental layers where embryonic blood vessels are surrounded by trophoblast cells and maternal blood
